<paragraph blockId="11.[151,555,1210,1236]" box="[151,555,1210,1236]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">
<heading bold="true" box="[151,555,1210,1236]" fontSize="11" level="1" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" reason="1">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,555,1210,1236]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">
Key to the groups of 
<taxonomicName authorityName=": Orchymont" authorityYear="1933" box="[412,555,1210,1236]" class="Insecta" family="Epimetopidae" genus="Epimetopus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[412,555,1210,1236]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Epimetopus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="11" pageNumber="12" type="key">
<keyStep pageId="11" pageNumber="12">
<paragraph blockId="11.[151,1436,1281,2035]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">
<keyLead pageId="11" pageNumber="12">
1 Small to very small species (ca. 
<quantity box="[532,675,1281,1302]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.75" metricValueMax="2.25" metricValueMin="1.25" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" unit="mm" value="1.75" valueMax="2.25" valueMin="1.25">1.25–2.25 mm</quantity>
); pronotum and elytra usually reddish, head dark brown to piceous, elytra without fascia (e.g., 
<figureCitation box="[380,484,1310,1331]" captionStart="FIGURES 8–11" captionStartId="12.[151,264,1728,1751]" captionTargetBox="[263,1347,203,1699]" captionTargetId="figure-88@12.[240,1348,195,1707]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIGURES 8–11. Epimetopus holotypes, dorsal and lateral habitus, and perpendicular to pronotum." pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Figs. 8–11</figureCitation>
); pronotum with, at most, minute secondary lobes; eye with incomplete canthus; aedeagus simple, without dorsal processes (e.g., 
<figureCitation box="[521,635,1340,1361]" captionStart="FIGURES 12–15" captionStartId="14.[151,264,1641,1664]" captionTargetBox="[175,1414,226,1578]" captionTargetId="figure-73@14.[151,1436,195,1619]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="FIGURES 12–15. Epimetopus, aedeagi of holotypes." pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Figs. 12–15</figureCitation>
)..................................................... 
<emphasis box="[1284,1368,1340,1361]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Costatus</emphasis>
Group
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="11.[151,1436,1281,2035]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">
<keyLead pageId="11" pageNumber="12">
1' Usually larger species (ca. 2.00– 
<quantity box="[543,632,1369,1390]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.7" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" unit="mm" value="3.7">3.70 mm</quantity>
, but seldom less than 
<quantity box="[850,940,1369,1390]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.25" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" unit="mm" value="2.25">2.25 mm</quantity>
); head, pronotum and elytra usually dark brown to piceous, elytra often with lighter V-shaped fascia (e.g., 
<figureCitation box="[756,835,1398,1419]" captionStart="FIGURE 82" captionStartId="46.[151,250,1726,1749]" captionTargetBox="[222,1370,226,1674]" captionTargetId="figure-140@46.[195,1393,193,1705]" captionTargetPageId="46" captionText="FIGURE 82. Epimetopus peruvianus holotype, dorsal and lateral habitus, and perpendicular to pronotum." pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Figs. 82</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[846,885,1398,1419]" captionStart="FIGURE 107" captionStartId="69.[151,250,1728,1751]" captionTargetBox="[227,1355,213,1689]" captionTargetId="figure-102@69.[203,1384,195,1707]" captionTargetPageId="69" captionText="FIGURE 107. Epimetopus lanceolatus holotype, dorsal and lateral habitus, and perpendicular to pronotum." pageId="11" pageNumber="12">107</figureCitation>
); pronotum with small to large secondary lobes; eye with canthus incomplete or complete; aedeagus with or without dorsal processes....................................... 2
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<keyStep pageId="11" pageNumber="12">
<paragraph blockId="11.[151,1436,1281,2035]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">
<keyLead pageId="11" pageNumber="12">
2 Eye with canthus incomplete; size ca. 
<quantity box="[615,761,1457,1478]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.9" metricValueMax="3.2" metricValueMin="2.6" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" unit="mm" value="2.9" valueMax="3.2" valueMin="2.6">2.60–3.20 mm</quantity>
; pronotum with secondary lobes very small; pronotal hood carinae grooved (e.g., 
<figureCitation box="[364,443,1486,1507]" captionStart="FIGURE 73" captionStartId="39.[151,250,1608,1631]" captionTargetBox="[157,1422,186,1584]" captionTargetId="figure-190@39.[151,1436,157,1587]" captionTargetPageId="39" captionText="FIGURE 73. Epimetopus graniger holotype, dorsal and lateral habitus, and perpendicular to pronotum." pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Figs. 73</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[453,480,1486,1507]" captionStart="FIGURE 78" captionStartId="42.[151,250,2001,2024]" captionTargetBox="[178,1411,492,1965]" captionTargetId="figure-90@42.[151,1436,471,1978]" captionTargetPageId="42" captionText="FIGURE 78. Epimetopus angulatus holotype, dorsal and lateral habitus, and perpendicular to pronotum." pageId="11" pageNumber="12">78</figureCitation>
); aedeagus with extendable hooks near apex of median lobe (e.g., 
<figureCitation box="[1116,1230,1486,1507]" captionStart="FIGURES79–80" captionStartId="44.[151,258,1995,2018]" captionTargetBox="[366,1220,525,1983]" captionTargetId="figure-149@44.[347,1239,515,1999]" captionTargetPageId="44" captionText="FIGURES79–80. Epimetopus angulatus aedeagus,holotype.79.Detail of apex of median lobe.80.Aedeagus (after Fikáček et al.2011)." pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Figs. 79–80</figureCitation>
).... 
<emphasis box="[1285,1369,1486,1507]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Mendeli</emphasis>
Group
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="11.[151,1436,1281,2035]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">
<keyLead pageId="11" pageNumber="12">2' Eye with canthus complete; pronotum with secondary lobes small to large; pronotal hood carinae grooved or non-grooved; aedeagus without extendable hooks near apex of median lobe................................................... 3</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<keyStep pageId="11" pageNumber="12">
<paragraph blockId="11.[151,1436,1281,2035]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">
<keyLead pageId="11" pageNumber="12">
3 Aedeagus simple, without dorsal processes (e.g., 
<figureCitation box="[699,840,1574,1595]" captionStart="FIGURES 109–110" captionStartId="71.[151,264,1990,2013]" captionTargetBox="[484,1105,472,1951]" captionTargetId="figure-136@71.[472,1115,457,1969]" captionTargetPageId="71" captionText="FIGURES 109–110. Epimetopus, aedeagi of holotypes. 109. E. lanceolatus. 110. E. lanceolatulus." pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Figs. 109–110</figureCitation>
); pronotum with large secondary lobes; pronotal hood carinae not grooved........................................................................................... 4
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="11.[151,1436,1281,2035]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">
<keyLead pageId="11" pageNumber="12">
3' Aedeagus with dorsal processes on median lobe (e.g., 
<figureCitation box="[757,837,1633,1654]" captionStart="FIGURES 87–90" captionStartId="51.[151,263,1965,1988]" captionTargetBox="[293,1306,524,1951]" captionTargetId="figure-195@51.[273,1319,509,1974]" captionTargetPageId="51" captionText="FIGURES 87–90. Epimetopus, aedeagi. 87. E. thermarum, topotypical paratype. 88. E. arcuatus, holotype. 89. E. leechi (jr. synonym of E. balfourbrownei), holotype. 90. E. balfourbrownei, holotype (side view is of topotypical paratype)." pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Figs. 90</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[849,876,1633,1654]" captionStart="FIGURES 97–98" captionStartId="60.[151,264,1980,2003]" captionTargetBox="[361,1230,498,1936]" captionTargetId="figure-137@60.[332,1255,483,1957]" captionTargetPageId="60" captionText="FIGURES 97–98. Epimetopus, aedeagi of holotypes. 97. E. clypeatus. 98. E. surinamensis." pageId="11" pageNumber="12">98</figureCitation>
); pronotum with small to large secondary lobes; pronotal hood carinae grooved................................................................................... 5
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<keyStep pageId="11" pageNumber="12">
<paragraph blockId="11.[151,1436,1281,2035]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">
<keyLead pageId="11" pageNumber="12">
4 Dorsum strongly tuberculate (
<figureCitation box="[512,596,1692,1713]" captionStart="FIGURE 124" captionStartId="84.[151,250,1726,1749]" captionTargetBox="[203,1388,229,1693]" captionTargetId="figure-157@84.[178,1409,193,1705]" captionTargetPageId="84" captionText="FIGURE 124. Epimetopus tuberculatus holotype, dorsal and lateral habitus, and perpendicular to pronotum." pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Fig. 124</figureCitation>
); pronotal hood carinae not confluent anteriorly; pronotal hood emarginate anteriorly...................................................................................... 
<emphasis box="[1244,1368,1721,1742]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Tuberculatus</emphasis>
Group
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="11.[151,1436,1281,2035]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">
<keyLead pageId="11" pageNumber="12">
4' Dorsum strongly carinate, but not tuberculate (e.g., 
<figureCitation box="[724,865,1750,1771]" captionStart-0="FIGURE 107" captionStart-1="FIGURE 108" captionStartId-0="69.[151,250,1728,1751]" captionStartId-1="70.[151,250,1870,1893]" captionTargetBox-0="[227,1355,213,1689]" captionTargetBox-1="[268,1336,356,1835]" captionTargetId-0="figure-102@69.[203,1384,195,1707]" captionTargetId-1="figure-141@70.[237,1351,337,1849]" captionTargetPageId-0="69" captionTargetPageId-1="70" captionText-0="FIGURE 107. Epimetopus lanceolatus holotype, dorsal and lateral habitus, and perpendicular to pronotum." captionText-1="FIGURE 108. Epimetopus lanceolatulus holotype, dorsal and lateral habitus, and perpendicular to pronotum." pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Figs. 107–108</figureCitation>
); pronotal hood carinae confluent anteriorly; pronotal hood sharply rounded anteriorly................................................................ 
<emphasis box="[1251,1368,1780,1801]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Lanceolatus</emphasis>
Group
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<keyStep pageId="11" pageNumber="12">
<paragraph blockId="11.[151,1436,1281,2035]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">
<keyLead pageId="11" pageNumber="12">
5 Aedeagus with dorsal processes short, wide basally and pointed apically (e.g., 
<figureCitation box="[976,1118,1809,1830]" captionStart="FIGURES 103–106" captionStartId="67.[151,264,1780,1803]" captionTargetBox="[225,1365,240,1679]" captionTargetId="figure-110@67.[205,1381,223,1735]" captionTargetPageId="67" captionText="FIGURES 103–106. Epimetopus, aedeagi of holotypes." pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Figs. 103–106</figureCitation>
); pronotum with secondary lobes very small............................................................................. 
<emphasis box="[1263,1368,1838,1859]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Plaumanni</emphasis>
Group
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="11.[151,1436,1281,2035]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">
<keyLead pageId="11" pageNumber="12">
5' Aedeagus with dorsal processes long and slender, often with apices with ridges (e.g., 
<figureCitation box="[1045,1124,1868,1889]" captionStart="FIGURE 91" captionStartId="53.[151,250,1683,1706]" captionText="FIGURE 91. Epimetopus thermarum, aedeagal variants." pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Figs. 91</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[1134,1173,1868,1889]" captionStart="FIGURE 112" captionStartId="74.[151,250,1675,1698]" captionText="FIGURE 112. Epimetopus trogoides, aedeagus of holotype." pageId="11" pageNumber="12">112</figureCitation>
); pronotum with secondary lobes small to large.................................................................................... 6
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<keyStep pageId="11" pageNumber="12">
<paragraph blockId="11.[151,1436,1281,2035]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">
<keyLead pageId="11" pageNumber="12">
6 Pronotum with very small secondary lobes (e.g., 
<figureCitation box="[695,775,1926,1947]" captionStart="FIGURE 86" captionStartId="50.[151,250,1962,1985]" captionTargetBox="[235,1348,474,1945]" captionTargetId="figure-153@50.[226,1361,455,1967]" captionTargetPageId="50" captionText="FIGURE 86. Epimetopus thermarum holotype, dorsal and lateral habitus, and perpendicular to pronotum." pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Figs. 86</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[785,812,1926,1947]" captionStart="FIGURE 95" captionStartId="58.[151,250,1894,1917]" captionTargetBox="[290,1293,400,1857]" captionTargetId="figure-118@58.[275,1312,383,1872]" captionTargetPageId="58" captionText="FIGURE 95. Epimetopus clypeatus holotype, dorsal and lateral habitus, and perpendicular to pronotum." pageId="11" pageNumber="12">95</figureCitation>
); aedeagus with dorsal processes attaching to median lobe proximal to its midlength (e.g., 
<figureCitation box="[478,594,1956,1977]" captionStart="FIGURES 97–98" captionStartId="60.[151,264,1980,2003]" captionTargetBox="[361,1230,498,1936]" captionTargetId="figure-137@60.[332,1255,483,1957]" captionTargetPageId="60" captionText="FIGURES 97–98. Epimetopus, aedeagi of holotypes. 97. E. clypeatus. 98. E. surinamensis." pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Figs. 97, 98</figureCitation>
); usually smaller species (ca. 
<quantity box="[880,1021,1956,1977]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.425" metricValueMax="2.75" metricValueMin="2.1" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" unit="mm" value="2.425" valueMax="2.75" valueMin="2.1">2.10–2.75 mm</quantity>
)................... 
<emphasis box="[1255,1368,1956,1977]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Thermarum</emphasis>
Group
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="11.[151,1436,1281,2035]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">
<keyLead pageId="11" pageNumber="12">
6' Pronotum with large (five species) or small (
<taxonomicName authorityName="Perkins" authorityYear="2012" box="[658,750,1985,2006]" class="Insecta" family="Epimetopidae" genus="Epimetopus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tridens">
<emphasis box="[658,750,1985,2006]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">E. tridens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) secondary lobes (e.g., 
<figureCitation box="[982,1071,1985,2006]" captionStart="FIGURE 111" captionStartId="73.[151,250,1944,1967]" captionTargetBox="[219,1389,459,1917]" captionTargetId="figure-128@73.[198,1389,411,1923]" captionTargetPageId="73" captionText="FIGURE 111. Epimetopus trogoides holotype, dorsal and lateral habitus, and perpendicular to pronotum." pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Figs. 111</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[1083,1120,1985,2006]" captionStart="FIGURE 118" captionStartId="81.[151,250,1908,1931]" captionTargetBox="[177,1421,428,1887]" captionTargetId="figure-179@81.[151,1436,413,1893]" captionTargetPageId="81" captionText="FIGURE 118. Epimetopus tridens holotype, dorsal and lateral habitus, and perpendicular to pronotum." pageId="11" pageNumber="12">118</figureCitation>
); aedeagus with dorsal processes attaching to median lobe distal to its midlength (e.g., 
<figureCitation box="[716,803,2014,2035]" captionStart="FIGURE 112" captionStartId="74.[151,250,1675,1698]" captionText="FIGURE 112. Epimetopus trogoides, aedeagus of holotype." pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Figs. 112</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[812,850,2014,2035]" captionStart="FIGURE 116" captionStartId="78.[151,250,1977,2000]" captionText="FIGURE 116. Epimetopus clandestinus, aedeagus of holotype." pageId="11" pageNumber="12">116</figureCitation>
); usually larger species (ca. 
<quantity box="[1108,1248,2014,2035]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.075" metricValueMax="3.65" metricValueMin="2.5" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" unit="mm" value="3.075" valueMax="3.65" valueMin="2.5">2.50–3.65 mm</quantity>
).. 
<emphasis box="[1273,1368,2014,2035]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Trogoides</emphasis>
Group
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
</subSubSection>
